english:
  title: A Record of the Gathering at Blue Stone Grotto
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On the sixth month, the day of Gapsin, the imperial envoy Huang Gong and his retinue departed for the capital. The Attendant-in-Waiting, the Marquis of Pyongyang, and the Attendant-in-Waiting, the Marquis of Sangnak, along with other nobles, saw them off as far as the Gold Stream Station, returning at midday. The season brought oppressive heat, with flames of cloud rising fiercely. The clerks pitched a canopy by the stream at Blue Stone Grotto to escape the swelter.

    The nobles took their seats on chairs beside the flowing water. Wind drifted from all directions. Their bodies found ease, their spirits grew boundless—as though a lingering ailment had departed their very frames. High melodies rose and scattered. Wine cups floated round twice over. All the nobles grew bright with joy together.

    Before long, the Marquis of Pyongyang suddenly spoke: "This joy is indeed joyful, yet does it not exceed all bounds?"

    Jeong Do-jeon replied: "The work of a minister is burdensome. All responsibilities gather upon one body, ten thousand concerns crowd the mind, leaving the spirit confined and the will stagnant. Even the wise and discerning may fall into error and oversight. Thus Bi Chen, when planning affairs of state for the land of Zheng, would go out into the fields—for it is in stillness and solitude that wisdom blooms. Should not this gathering then help to release our pent-up spirits and guide our stalled wills toward clarity?"

    The nobles replied: "Your words ring true."

    Yet the Marquis of Pyongyang, having come here merely to see off a guest, upon witnessing their merriment, was moved to caution against excess. This too is worthy of remembrance. And so I set it down.
  footnotes:
    - 'Bi Chen (裨諶): A legendary minister of the State of Zheng known for receiving wise counsel from commoners he encountered in the countryside, exemplifying how informal settings and democratic exchange of ideas can yield better governance.'
    - The wine cups 'floating round' refers to the traditional practice of floating wine cups on a flowing stream, a common ritual among literati gatherings in East Asia.
